\meta{version}{"1.0"}

\meta{description}{Implement Zero Trust Network Access using Zscaler Private Access (ZPA) to replace traditional VPN with identity-based, context-aware access to private applications through the Zscaler Zero Trust Exchange.}

\subtree{
\title{Implementing Zero Trust Network Access with Zscaler}
\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Understanding of zero trust principles (NIST SP 800-207)}
\li{Familiarity with identity providers (Okta, Azure AD, Ping Identity)}
\li{Knowledge of network security fundamentals}
\li{Access to Zscaler Private Access (ZPA) tenant}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Zero Trust Network Access (ZTNA) replaces traditional VPN architectures by enforcing identity-based, context-aware access to private applications without placing users on the corporate network. Zscaler Private Access (ZPA) is a leading ZTNA solution that brokers secure connections between authenticated users and internal applications through the Zscaler Zero Trust Exchange cloud platform.}

\p{This skill covers end-to-end deployment of ZPA including connector setup, application segmentation, policy configuration, and integration with identity providers for continuous verification.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{When deploying or configuring implementing zero trust network access with zscaler capabilities in your environment}
\li{When establishing security controls aligned to compliance requirements}
\li{When building or improving security architecture for this domain}
\li{When conducting security assessments that require this implementation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Familiarity with zero trust architecture concepts and tools}
\li{Access to a test or lab environment for safe execution}
\li{Python 3.8+ with required dependencies installed}
\li{Appropriate authorization for any testing activities}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Architecture}
\subtree{
\title{Zscaler Private Access Components}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Client Connector}: Lightweight agent on user endpoints that establishes outbound TLS tunnels to the nearest ZPA Service Edge}
\li{\strong{ZPA Service Edge}: Cloud-hosted broker (or Private Service Edge on-premises) that stitches user-to-app connections after policy evaluation}
\li{\strong{App Connector}: Lightweight VM deployed in the application environment that creates outbound tunnels to the Service Edge}
\li{\strong{ZPA Admin Portal}: Centralized management console for defining applications, segments, and access policies}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Connection Flow}
\pre{\startverb
User Device (Client Connector)
    |
    v [Outbound TLS tunnel]
ZPA Service Edge (Policy Evaluation + IdP Auth)
    |
    v [Outbound TLS tunnel]
App Connector --> Internal Application
\stopverb}

\p{Key principle: No inbound connections are required. Both the Client Connector and App Connector initiate outbound-only connections, eliminating the attack surface of traditional VPNs.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\subtree{
\title{Application Segments}
\p{Define specific applications or groups of applications by IP address, FQDN, port, and protocol. Segments enable granular microsegmentation rather than broad network access.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Access Policies}
\p{Policies combine user identity, group membership, device posture, and contextual signals (location, time) to grant or deny access to application segments.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Server Groups}
\p{Logical groupings of App Connectors that serve specific application segments, enabling high availability and geographic distribution.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Browser Access}
\p{ZPA supports clientless browser-based access for web applications, enabling ZTNA for unmanaged devices and third-party users without requiring the Client Connector.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Phase 1: Foundation Setup}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Configure Identity Provider Integration}}
\li{Navigate to Administration > IdP Configuration in ZPA Admin Portal}
\li{Add SAML 2.0 or OIDC integration with your IdP (Azure AD, Okta, Ping)}
\li{Configure SCIM provisioning for automatic user/group synchronization}
\li{Test SSO authentication flow}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Deploy App Connectors}}
\li{Provision App Connector VMs in each application environment (data center, AWS VPC, Azure VNet)}
\li{Download the provisioning key from ZPA Admin Portal}
\li{Install and enroll the App Connector using the provisioning key}
\li{Verify connector status shows "Healthy" in the admin portal}
\li{Deploy at least two connectors per environment for high availability}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Create Server Groups}}
\li{Group App Connectors by geographic location or application tier}
\li{Configure health check intervals and failover behavior}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Application Segmentation}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Define Application Segments}}
\li{Create segments for each application or logical group}
\li{Specify domains/IPs, ports, and protocols}
\li{Associate segments with appropriate server groups}
\li{Enable or disable browser access as needed}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Create Segment Groups}}
\li{Organize application segments into logical groups (e.g., HR apps, Finance apps)}
\li{Use segment groups to simplify policy management}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Policy Configuration}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Configure Access Policies}}
\li{Define rules matching user groups to application segments}
\li{Apply conditions: device posture, client type, SAML attributes}
\li{Order rules by priority (most restrictive first)}
\li{Create deny rules for blocked access scenarios}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Enable Device Posture Checks}}
\li{Configure posture profiles requiring OS patch level, disk encryption, antivirus status}
\li{Integrate with endpoint management (CrowdStrike, Microsoft Intune, Carbon Black)}
\li{Associate posture profiles with access policies}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Client Deployment}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Deploy Client Connector}}
\li{Package the Zscaler Client Connector with enrollment token}
\li{Deploy via MDM (Intune, Jamf, SCCM) or manual installation}
\li{Configure forwarding profile to route private app traffic through ZPA}
\li{Test user authentication and application access}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 5: Monitoring and Optimization}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Enable Logging and Monitoring}}
\li{Configure log streaming to SIEM (Splunk, Sentinel, QRadar)}
\li{Set up alerts for policy violations, connector health, and authentication failures}
\li{Review ZPA Insights dashboard for usage analytics}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Iterative Refinement}}
\li{Analyze access logs to identify shadow IT and unauthorized access attempts}
\li{Refine application segments based on actual traffic patterns}
\li{Expand coverage from pilot applications to full enterprise deployment}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Validation Checklist}
\ul{
\li{[ ] Identity provider integration tested with SSO and SCIM sync}
\li{[ ] App Connectors deployed and showing healthy status in all environments}
\li{[ ] Application segments defined with correct IPs/FQDNs, ports, protocols}
\li{[ ] Access policies enforce least-privilege per user group}
\li{[ ] Device posture checks block non-compliant endpoints}
\li{[ ] Client Connector deployed to all managed endpoints}
\li{[ ] Log streaming to SIEM confirmed with test events}
\li{[ ] Failover tested by disabling one App Connector per server group}
\li{[ ] Browser Access configured for web apps requiring third-party access}
\li{[ ] VPN decommission plan documented with rollback procedures}
}
}

